    "## Conclusion & Key Takeaways\n",
    "\n",
    "### What We Learned:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Scikit-learn Advantages:**\n",
    "   - Quick to implement and train\n",
    "   - Excellent for tabular/structured data\n",
    "   - Provides built-in feature importance\n",
    "   - Generally interpretable\n",
    "   - Works well for traditional ML tasks\n",
    "\n",
    "2. **PyTorch Advantages:**\n",
    "   - More flexible architecture design\n",
    "   - Better for custom deep learning models\n",
    "   - Easier to implement advanced techniques (attention, etc.)\n",
    "   - Good scalability for GPU computing\n",
    "   - Better for image, text, and sequential data\n",
    "\n",
    "3. **Model Performance:**\n",
    "   - Both models achieved strong results on the test set\n",
    "   - Random Forest often performs well on tabular medical data\n",
    "   - Neural networks can match or exceed tree-based models with proper tuning\n",
    "\n",
    "4. **Best Practices:**\n",
    "   - Always normalize/scale features before training\n",
    "   - Split data into train/test sets to avoid overfitting\n",
    "   - Use appropriate evaluation metrics (accuracy, precision, recall, F1, AUC-ROC)\n",
    "   - Compare multiple models before choosing one for production\n",
    "   - Regular retraining with new data is crucial in medical applications\n",
    "\n",
    "### Further Improvements:\n",
    "- Hyperparameter tuning (GridSearchCV, Optuna)\n",
    "- Cross-validation for more robust evaluation\n",
    "- Handling class imbalance (if present)\n",
    "- Feature engineering and selection\n",
    "- Ensemble methods combining both models\n",
    "- Model interpretability techniques (SHAP, LIME)"
   ]
